    "body": "## Motivation\r\n\r\nMulti-Item Scoring (MIS) packs a query and multiple items into a single sequence (`query<delim>item1<delim>item2<delim>...`) for a single forward pass instead of N separate passes. The existing `--multi-item-scoring-delimiter` required callers to choose and pass a delimiter token ID, and the runtime scanned `input_ids` on the GPU to find delimiter positions at every stage (attention, logits, pooler), causing redundant work and implicit CUDA syncs from `.item()` and `.nonzero()` calls.\r\n\r\nThis PR replaces `--multi-item-scoring-delimiter <token_id>` with a simple `--enable-mis` boolean flag and pre-computes delimiter indices from item lengths, eliminating all runtime scanning and GPU-to-CPU syncs.\r\n\r\n## `--enable-mis` flag\r\n\r\n**Before** — callers had to pick a delimiter token ID and pass incompatible-setting flags manually:\r\n```bash\r\n--multi-item-scoring-delimiter 128009 --disable-radix-cache --chunked-prefill-size -1\r\n```\r\n\r\n**After** — a single boolean flag; required settings are auto-applied:\r\n```bash\r\n--enable-mis --attention-backend flashinfer\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe flag:\r\n- Hardcodes `MIS_DELIMITER_TOKEN_ID = 9999` as a placeholder token (exists only for FlashInfer attention mask compatibility and logprob column indexing — positions are determined by item lengths, not by scanning for this token)\r\n- **Auto-disables** CUDA graph, radix cache, and chunked prefill (with warnings)\r\n- **Asserts** `--attention-backend flashinfer` (not auto-changed since the backend choice is user-facing)\r\n- Removes the need for callers to know tokenizer-specific delimiter tokens\r\n\r\nAll MIS setup and validation is consolidated in `_handle_multi_item_scoring()`, which runs after other `_handle_*` helpers so the final config state is authoritative.\r\n\r\n## Pre-computed delimiter indices\r\n\r\nInstead of scanning `input_ids == delimiter` on the GPU at each stage, delimiter positions are computed once during tokenization from item lengths and piped through the request as CPU tensors:\r\n\r\n```\r\ntokenizer_manager_score_mixin  →  io_struct  →  scheduler  →  schedule_batch (CPU tensor)\r\n    →  forward_batch_info  →  flashinfer_backend / logits_processor / pooler\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe ScheduleBatch enforces batch consistency: if any request in a batch carries MIS indices, all must (asserted) — mixed MIS/non-MIS batches are rejected early with a clear error.\r\n\r\n### Consumers updated\r\n- **`flashinfer_backend.py`**: `_process_multi_item_scoring()` uses pre-computed CPU tensors + `torch.searchsorted` instead of `(input_ids == delim).nonzero()`. Uses `extend_prefix_lens_cpu` / `extend_seq_lens_cpu` to avoid GPU syncs.\r\n- **`logits_processor.py`**: `compute_logprobs_for_multi_item_scoring()` uses pre-computed indices to gather hidden states at delimiter positions. Builds offset-adjusted indices on CPU and does a single batched `.to(device)` transfer instead of per-request transfers.\r\n- **`pooler.py`**: new `pool_at_delimiter_positions()` helper replaces inline `input_ids` scanning. `score_and_pool()` now pools hidden states at pre-delimiter positions first, then scores only those tokens — preserves upstream's per-request `pooled_hidden_states` return feature while using pre-computed indices.\r\n- **`scheduler_output_processor_mixin.py`**: `_is_multi_item_scoring()` uses `enable_mis` + pre-computed indices instead of scanning `origin_input_ids`.\r\n\r\n## Tests\r\n- New `test/registered/prefill_only/test_multi_item_scoring.py` with CI registration — 6 test classes: ServerArgs validation, generation MIS, classification MIS (pre-trained model), parity, classification parity, and advanced (distinctness, determinism, concurrency).\r\n- Updated `test_score_api.py`, `test_score_engine.py`, `test_embed_overrides.py`, `test_pooled_hidden_states.py` to use `--enable-mis` / `enable_mis=True`.\r\n- Unit test `test_pooler_score_and_pool.py` exercises `pool_at_delimiter_positions` and the MIS path of `score_and_pool` on CPU — no GPU required.\r\n\r\nCo-authored-by: Chanh Nguyen <chanhnguyen@gmail.com>\r\nCo-authored-by: Sundara Raman Ramachandran <sundar24295@gmail.com>\r\n",
